Inflation has dropped food in Europe
The accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the price rise, in the 13 countries of the euro area, was more significant than forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 percent was recorded, the European Community Statistics Office located in Luxembourg said.
The official forecasts showed only 3 percent, Bloomberg.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the direct interest rate by saying that the decrease of interest, with the rise of raw materials prices and the decrease of unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationist spiral.
The ECB wants to keep inflation below but close to 2 percent.
According to an analyst, it is the Catch 22 for the ECB: “We need to dissuade” inflation so that we no longer have to intervene on this issue later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 percent is a record in the last twelve years and in Spain, it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has decreased due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
The long-term cereal market rates have risen by 88 percent and the soya price has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased considerably in 2007.
This year, the world oil price rose by 52 percent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 this year to 2.5 percent but, in 2009, it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the inflation rate for 12 months remains around 3 percent, however, in the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to decrease the direct rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates a government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of Fidesz (Young Democrats Alliance) supporters has increased significantly in early December. So since 2002, it currently has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Institute of Survey) has never previously found such a low socialist support, namely 13 percent.
For faithful voters, the difference would represent, due to the greatest determination of opposition voters, a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of a fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the survey, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the parliamentary threshold: their support is 2% in the entire population.
On faithful voters some to go to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate continued to deteriorate compared to the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who judged the country’s economic situation was severe has never been so high, it rises to 41 percent and according to 46 percent complementary the situation is quite severe.
After the more optimistic prospects of last spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For the next year, the majority of the population predicts an aggravation and only one tenth predicts an improvement in the situation.
In December last year, 71% of the respondents, a majority never seen in Gallup’s previous surveys, found that the prime minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 per cent don’t trust the prime minister at all and 27 per cent don’t trust the Fidesz president at all.
One of the indicators of the change of political situation is the proportion of society thinking that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be treated without government change.
While after the outbreaks last October, 35 percent of respondents wanted the government and the prime minister to remain in office, the current rate is only 20 percent.
On the question about the intention of voting, 60 percent of the respondents answered that they would definitely go to vote and the 20 percent added said that they would probably go to vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to organize next Sunday", only 55 percent of respondents would participate and 15 percent additional would probably participate.
74 percent of people would say no to the fees for higher education, 79 percent would say no to the consultation costs and 84 percent would say no to the hospitalization costs.
When we only look at the same proportions among the people who expressed their intention to vote for the referendum, respectively 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of registration rights, consultation fees and hospitalization fees.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has raised its prices by twenty percent
The hypermarkets located in the Budaörs trade triangleined the average price rise of 16 percent from last year, unlike this year the VAT rate did not rise.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Dayly Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent in average, a value increase significantly greater than a thousand forints appeared in all hypermarkets.
The prices, “which had already flown” in the major food stores in December last year, have no longer increased brutally compared to the previous high base.
However, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased significantly below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded 91 forints, at least the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10 573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6 800 forints.)
The prices of Unicum and living fish remained almost the same as last year, but the prices of dwarf, nuts and pavot have increased significantly.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data from the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics), but at Auchan, we found bread from a kilogram to only 139 forints.
The competition did not lower the product price below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the recorded bottle of two liters of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the recorded bottle included.
Unfortunately this year, in terms of daily basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its daily basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
By comparing last year’s most expensive basket and this year’s cheapest basket, we see a gap of 12 percent while the difference between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive basket is 21 percent.
Prices have risen by 1 480 forints in average.
Last year, prices increased by an average of 1,206 forints, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticed in the Christmas prices of last year.
This process made trade confusing, the hypermarkets were unable to clearly determine what margin to apply to products as long as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he risks to lose a large profit on the margin suited to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the price increase of the daily basket evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1 720 forints higher than the value of 2006 while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the most expensive basket was higher than 1.630 forints than last year and the cheapest prices increased by 1.284 forints too.
By approaching the two Christmas seasons, we saw a catastrophic rise in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumption items rose by more than 30 percent in the hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH data: for some first-need foods, the Statistical Institute found a price increase of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with milk and eggs.)
According to the last’s daily basket, this seems almost absurd as the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has just increased by just more than 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indicators, flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to make the brutal price rise also accepted by multinational companies.
In the commercial gold triangle, the hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experience, most customers no longer look at the prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take foods of long conservation by palettes.
On Wednesday morning, major tails formed in the treasury’s three hypermarkets as the number of customers has grown suddenly.
But, according to our information, the turnover is less important in the province, many multinational companies complain to survey companies not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals make savings on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mostly caused by misuse of antibiotics, were recorded in hospitals.
The hygiene conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overload of medical staff don’t help block infections, says the chief physician of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also make the economy on disinfectants
Not long ago a MRSA infection was diagnosed at the traumatology service of the János Hospital.
The antibiotic resistant bacteria was detected on a man hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The wounded in a serious car accident left the hospital but shortly after he had to return there due to a MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to do him an important operation due to the bacteria that is in his body.
Until December 10, this year, 1,094 hospitalized infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen were to the National Nosocomial Monitoring System, said Karolina Böröcz, the chief physician of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Know that it is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSAs, otherwise staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One-third of people are carryers of the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) react well to antibiotics, they are easily healable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which react well to antibiotics, will develop a bacteria well-resistant to antibiotics that will quickly proliferate in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged dysfunction of the immune system, this bacteria can cause serious hospital infections, such as a traumatic infection or septicemia, on elderly, low-weight or weakened bodies.
According to the director of the János Hospital, there is nothing special in MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily lives of hospitals.
The most important thing is not to confuse the infection with the epidemic, you don’t find MRSA only or you don’t look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
They are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, the care staff put rubber gloves and protective masks and we have suitable antibiotics to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are MRSA carriers, however the infection cannot always be avoided.
The sampling is not fashionable.
The vast majority of the infections caused by MRSA could be prevented but the current conditions and circumstances are not favorable, in Hungarian hospitals, to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection is mainly manifested in hospitals and resorts for elderly people, hospitals should control hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients carrying MRSA.
However, microbiological removal is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases only occur if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the head doctor of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian guidelines also for the healing of certain infections and syndrome.
It is necessary to make efforts to target antibiotic therapy, otherwise, microbiological examinations should be carried out in order to prevent drug resistance but hospitals do not always take it into account.
The realization of microbiological screening is even more rare in ambulatory and basic care, Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals make savings on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs spread from one patient to another most often through medical staff.
Therefore, it is essential to wash your hands, put gloves and protective masks. However, significant lacunes are detected in hospitals also in this area.
MRSAs spread by infection transmitted by inhalation of drops and by contact. However, due to the conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemic, the patients should be distant from each other at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in difficult financial situation, make savings on disinfectants, they lack nurses, the sick are many, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are observed, the number of infections is lower in a detrimental way or then the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government Projects Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for social security funds, so we are fighting this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has set up a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSAs.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) shows among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
