Additional €400 million for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three agreements of a total value of €400 million on a credit line to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of €300 million for Hungarian budget financing of transport and environmental projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund whose €100 million credit agreement has already been signed by the parties.
The credit agreement of €150 million also concerns the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of €300 million for Hungary, the remaining €150 million will be used later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a contract of €50 million for innovation, the state budget will use this package first in the framework of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During negotiations, the project of line 4 of the metro was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would re-debat the possible modification of the initial contract when Hungary has completed the details of the funding of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has allocated a total of €8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB gives its credits according to the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grant period of eight years and without commitment commission.
