Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to the communication of Environment and Water Minister Gábor Fodor, the meetings of professionals will end on Tuesday, however, on Wednesday, after the official opening, the ministers’ negotiations on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians coming from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap to define efforts to do after the emission reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
Currently, there is a strong discussion on this issue between developing countries and developed countries.
The United States also that, for the moment, they do not want to discuss accurate figures, although they are ready to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent by 2020 compared to the level of 1990.
Another important topic of the conference is to see if developed countries are committed, in addition to emissions reduction, to provide financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
A agreement has also been signed on the aid to be provided to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a board of directors consisting of 16 members probably within the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF), Piac és Profit (Market and Profit) said.
6% of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister of Environment and Water, Gábor Fodor, confirms the ambition of the EU to keep its role as Admiral vessel in global efforts aimed at protecting the climate and encouraging the signature of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent before 2020 compared to the level reached in 1990, regardless of the success of the signing of the 2012 Agreement, and was ready to reduce them to 30 percent if the other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also willing to take commitments adapted to their responsibility and capacity.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the countries signing the Kyoto Protocol had aimed at a total reduction of 5.2 percent and all 15 EU members at that time took the commitment of 8 percent less.
Hungary has undertaken to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, reminds the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The challenge is big in Bali because the long-term international climate policy agreement must be implemented within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would be postponed after 2012. In this case, the commitments to reduction below the values provided for in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system whose need was emphasized in the new IPCC report, the international scientific body, which won the Nobel Peace Prize of the United Nations, responsible for taking care of climate change.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the average Earth temperature rise of more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army Recruits on YouTube
The units of the British army, on the video sharing site, report recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in order to become popular.
First, it is the British Air Force (RAF) that has been passionate about YouTube: the special units intervening in Afghanistan upload videos on the operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken with the help of miniature cameras set on the helmet, are monitored at the air force operations headquarters in Kandahar and they are then transferred to London or compatriots charge them on the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
The air force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net through this path and their “chain” has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Defence Ministry registered under the name of "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and broadcasts videos about the operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peace Maintenance Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission in Afghanistan
According to the initial goal of the air force, the videos were passed on the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defense, they also served to make the public aware of the real goals of the army’s presence abroad.
The propaganda published by this path does not cost practically anything compared to the usual recruitment ads posted on television, according to the BBC Gordon Mackenzie, defense consultant. In contrast, it also inevitably carries a political message since it justifies in a special form the well-founded military operations decided by the government.
The Americans have a game.
The army is troubled because, in addition to the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos are passed on the sharing site that also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the “official” propaganda films, slightly hypocritic, officers do not avoid talking about losses but they never present the bloody side of the battle.
Moreover, many videos had already passed on the net showing the operating zones in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out in real mission, but the British army has been packing for the upload of these videos only recently.
The Americans make the recruitment a little differently by using the America's Army shooting game that can be downloaded for free. In this game the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
