Mega strike forces gather
The Syndicates of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will form their strike committee on Friday, which will be charged with coordinating Monday's unlimited strike.
On Saturday, a general assembly of protest will be held and on Monday, on the day of the final vote on the health care funds law, the strike will begin.
This action will surely cause significant locks in the traffic as rail traffic will be almost completely stopped and BKV (public transport company) employees will also make a strike until 13:00.
The League Syndicates will announce, Friday afternoon, the details of their Monday strike, organized with the National Association of Workers' Councils.
The LIGA-MOSZ strike committee will also be formed, it will serve as the coordinator of Monday’s actions.
On Saturday, a general assembly of protest will be held and, from Monday, the organizations joining the strike will stop the work for an indefinite period if they fail to find an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, starting from the day of the vote in parliament on the health care funds law, is not defined.
If the National Assembly fails to adopt the law on health funds, the syndicates will immediately withdraw the call to the strike.
However, if the law is voted, the strike committees will meet and decide what to follow.
According to the national assembly’s Monday agenda, it is likely that the vote on the health care funds law will take place only late at night or even at night.
Due to the scheduled strike on Monday, significant closures are planned in the traffic: railways will stop the work for an indefinite period and in the morning part of public transport in Budapest and more than half of Volán companies are at risk of being stopped.
At the same time, in different points of the country, half of the road will also be blocked.
Many trade unions and civil organizations have joined the call to the strike, the list of them is constantly updated on the League site.
Some organizations report to make the strike for an indefinite period, while others have declared a temporary stop of work.
Until Thursday afternoon the MÁV (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Trailer Syndicate (VDSZSZ) failed to find an agreement on the minimum services, gold, at the approaching of Christmas holidays, more and more are those taking the train.
According to current communications, Budapest’s public transport will make a strike from the start of service until 13h, Budapest airport between 7h and 9h in the morning, the League’s Electricity and Thermal Energy Industrial Syndicates will make a four-hour strike, the Teachers’ Syndicate and the Democratic Teachers’ Syndicate have called for a strike respectively for 2 hours and from 2h to 8h.
The National Association of Doctors will make a two-hour warning strike throughout the country, the Health and Social Sector Employees Syndicate (EDDSZ) associated with SZEF will make a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four claims, formulated by the League, requires the government to withdraw its proposal on the health reform and submit a new concept to the social debate.
The second claim requires that the new pension calculation method to be implemented from the next year be introduced in several stages.
The third claim requires a guarantee, in terms of retirement before the legal age, which would allow the functions that deserve it to be passed into the system before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Trailer Syndicate (VDSZSZ), associated with the League Syndicates, of the Ministry of Economy and Transport proposal on secondary railways and the waiting for another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases Country Risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital (Risk Analysing Division), the activity of the Hungarian Guard, established in August last year, with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért Mozgalom (Movement for a Better Hungary) increases, in several aspects, the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its “risk warning”, the company points out that, in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is already that “in the short term aggressive ethnic confrontations can occur as a result of the aggravation of the already existing ethnic tension between the Tzigan and non-Tzigan population of Hungary.”
The research institution added that the Hungarian Guard’s political strategy that is likely to cause this situation is the main reason for this.
As they say, this is explained by one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors: “the public actors have passed the public debate on the Rom affair to representatives of radical and extreme political unions that have based a political strategy on the dispute between the Zygan and the Hungarians.”
The problem is worsening, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are stronger and the arrival of aggressive conflicts is more likely, they say.
But, according to the research institut, under the effect of the increased attention of Hungarian and international media, the activity of the Hungarian Guard “significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, regarding the confidence in the stability and democratic maturity of the country.”
They remind that, following a greater advertisement given to the reorganization of Hungarian radical and extreme right-wing groups since autumn 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since summer 2007 giving itself the name of “National Self-Defense Association”.
“The common trait of these assemblies is that they define themselves as a civil organization while they publicly declare the preparation of their members for defence missions (catastrophes, national defence, defence of order), armed if necessary, in addition, referring to the inability of the police, of the army, otherwise of the state,” they added.
They that everything was going according to the method that, based on the ranker of the society of politics and parties, seeks to disguise different political ambitions under a civil aspect.
The emphasis on civility and association status therefore serves only to avoid legal traps from the registration of these associations in the court but they also constitute a political strategy.
The analysis indicates that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor that also increases the risk compared to neighbouring relations.
“In recent months, many neighboring countries have cited the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of risk, and ultranationalist political actors in some neighboring countries want to justify their anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the constitution of the Hungarian Guard.
This affects the political stability of the region,” they added.
