Banks want to resolve the crisis
The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian central banks have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than $100 billion will be placed on the monetary markets through auctions.
It will be for banks to sell, through an auction system, the interest rates to which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the U.S. Fed will send $40 billion to the auctions and, in addition, it will provide $24 billion to the European and Swiss Central Banks.
This is the first time since the September 11 attacks that the central banks of individual states have decided to take such a concerted action to prevent or even reduce the effects of the financial crisis.
“This approach tends to solve the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could borrow,” says Bernard Baumohl of the Economic Outlook Group’s customer report.
“The concerted action of the Central Banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to approximately 50 percent,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to non-refunded loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts are expecting more billion losses.
"If the central banks have chosen this approach, it is that they have to really understand what can still be followed," said ABN chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
“It seems that the situation is really bad,” he adds.
Central banks fear that if the banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will borrow more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and dive the U.S. economy into a recession that could influence global economic growth.
The central banks made this choice after it failed to lower the London interbank rate, called LIBOR, used to borrow on the interbank market.
This means that the banks were still afraid of mutual loans, despite the fact that the U.S., Canadian and English central banks had decreased their interest rates several times during the autumn.
“This will have the same effect as a new fall in interest rates,” said Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting to Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that the approach of the Central Banks will not contribute to conjuring the crisis, as it does not solve the main problem that is the fall of the real estate market in the US.
