A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which track the destins of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million archive documents, stored on 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far consultable only for a “humanitarian” purpose, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of a former victim or its rightholders.
The eleven states responsible for their management – including Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening is effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will enable research “in particular on the movements of prisoners, the population of camps and the health status of forced workers,” explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, opposed the public opening of these nominative documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or the arrest mandates established by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find the civilians deported or subjected to mandatory work and, if possible, to provide them with evidence of their internation, in order to open the way to their compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for some of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen has a limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” said in 2006 Pr Wolfgang Benz, director of the Centre for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität of Berlin.
