Venus is the hell twin of the earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like Earth than ever thought: the European spacecraft "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind turbines at the poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightings on Venus.
The European "Venus Express" spacecraft today proved it - it detected electromagnetic waves at the boundary of the atmosphere: the light on Venus blows at an altitude of approximately 56 kilometers of cloud cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous cyprine theory, the lightning would have made life appear on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that have led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: "If life was there, it must have been at a very old date of history," says Sean Solomon of the "Carnegie Institution" in Washington.
Today there should be little living things on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times thinner than on Earth, sometimes there are temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus is the hell twin of the Earth, but it remains a twin," Russel said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and dimensions, has been hit by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venus research, since no more spots were on the way to explore this planet since the 1980s.
According to the researchers, the latest research results that have now been presented in several "Nature" articles not only emphasize the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the common points with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more than expected at first.
Thus, the researchers found, in addition to the wind turbines already known in the North Pole, a cloud turbine in the South Pole, which turns even much faster.
The phenomenon reminds the air currents in the Earth’s hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Institute di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica Italy.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet called a night or morning star turns around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much slower on itself: a Venus day lasts 243 terrestrial days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, does not much remind Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed in similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed on Earth in the form of carbonate, it constitutes on Venus the largest part of the atmosphere.
