Whoever connects the concepts of Sweden and wood box, thinks of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Or if so?
Currently, wooden boxes made in Sweden throw shadows on Warhol's list of works.
A large part of the eighty Brillo-Boxs of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeit.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned a few months ago the authenticity of the 1968 Brillo-Boxs by Andy Warhol, the internal research of the Moderna Museet of Stockholm today ends to a disappointing result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", the former director of the museum Pontus Hulten gave in 1995 to the Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as a large part of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Type Stockholm", which circulate on the international art market.
The ancient history is overwhelmed, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created in New York its first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powder soap cartons.
A exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo carton-made boxes: These were not (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were directly delivered from the Brillo carton factory.
It was not artwork here, but rather their patterns, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today about about fifteen wooden boxes that at the time would be entering the history of art and auctions, as the original Brillo-Boxes authorized by Andy Warhol, with the title "Type Stockholm".
Some of them reached more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the museum Pontus Hultén wrongly claimed later that about a hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would then have ceded him.
In fact, the 105 Hultén boxes were produced in Malmö only in 1990, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol was already dead for three years.
Lars Byström, the chief conservator of the Moderna Museet, examined, alongside the six Brillo-Boxes of the museum, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their stratified panels were first printed and poncated, then applied with a pince of the paint with white oil.
The texture of the copies that date from the 1990s, on the contrary, reveals that the paint was directly applied without layer of background on stratified panels, using a paint roll - in addition, it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
“These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol’s Brillo-Boxes,” says director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: “If the ‘Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board’ in New York does not make another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material.”
Also in July the Authentication Board announced, of course, that it would investigate the “hard accusations” that will be raised in the case of powder soap boxes.
From then on, there was an inexorable silence.
